":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dafydd ap Madog was born about 1317, in Llangyniew, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Madog ap Dafydd, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Madog ap Dafydd, was 25. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gwenllian ferch Hywel."},"et":{"ABT    1317–":"umbes 1317–Surnud","1317–Male":"1317–Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1292–1315":"1292–1315","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1315":"1315","1435":"1435","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1342":"1342","ABT    1317":"umbes 1317","1293":"1293","about 1342":"umbes 1342","1292":"1292","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","of Cynhinfa,Llangynyw,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Llangyniew, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","Wales":"Wales","of Caerdegog,Llanfechell,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1317–":"noin 1317–Kuollut","1317–Male":"1317–Kuollut","1319–Male":"1319–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1342–Female":"1342–Kuollut","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1292–